EXTRACTED VALUE: If you're after a basketball game for the Santa stocking though, NBA 2K7 is by far the best choice this year.
We've actually been waiting for this game for years, ever since people started coining the term, "next-gen." Thankfully, that time has finally come.
A few rough spots, but the "ultimate" in the game's name is no exaggeration.
The astounding level of variety that is packed into the game is wonderful to see.
You're in for one hell of a good time. [Oct 2007, p.108]
Some questionable story elements aside, the game is enjoyable and manages to maintain a fairly consistent pace throughout.
The Enchanted Forest is outlined in such vibrant colors, you'll want to check to see if your screen is actually dripping with paint.
Pure is the new kid on the block, and if given a sequel or two to improve, it could grow into a brilliant beast of a man.
Minor gripes aside, Homecourt is a deliciously addictive baller and a commendable next-gen Street effort on EA's part.
This game is little more than a lowbrow, yet humorous, thug-life simulator.
Don't worry about hesitating to spend the $60, you will spend more time than you think playing this game.
The first truly "next-gen" Tony Hawk game looks and plays great.
The improved accessibility is welcome, the deepened career mode is great and the overall presentation quality can't be overlooked.
Silky smooth graphics accompany spot-on controls.
A bit pricey for a game so close to "Bejeweled," but the RPG element genuinely adds to the package. [Christmas 2007, p.98]
At the very least, it's the best-looking and -playing open-world game this side of "Oblivion" on the X360 right now.
